  <feedback condition="$ans1.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans1.creditAchieved != 1">Your answer will be an integer value.
  </feedback>




<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example newNameSpace>
<p><em>Convert the angle <m>\alpha = \frac{\pi}{9}</m> radians to degrees.</em></p>
  
<p><alert><em>Solution.</em></alert></p>
<p>If you recall the one fact that <m>180^{\circ}</m> is the same as <m>\pi</m> radians, you will always remember the unit fraction required for conversion: <m>\frac{180}{\pi}</m>. Multiply by this <term>unit fraction</term><footnote>A unit fraction is a fraction whose value is equal to <m>1</m>. They are often used for conversions between different units.</footnote> to convert any angle from radians to degrees:
  <me>\frac{\pi}{9} = \frac{\pi}{9} \left(\frac{180}{\pi}\right) = 20^{\circ}</me></p>
</example>

<p>
<ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/precalculus/chapter/topic-1-3/">Textbook link: The Radian Measure of an Angle</ref>
</p>

  
<!-- <p><em><alert>How to check your answer</alert></em>: </p> -->
</hint>

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
<m>$a^{\circ}</m>
</solution>
</problem>




